This article is a memorandum from the White House Office of the Press Secretary, dated February 28, 2012. The memorandum is addressed to the Secretary of the Interior and discusses the proposed revised habitat for the spotted owl and the goal of minimizing regulatory burdens. The memorandum emphasizes the need to consider economic considerations, national security impact, and other relevant factors when designating critical habitat for the spotted owl. It also highlights the importance of flexibility and pragmatism in the proposed rule, including potential exclusions of private lands and State lands from critical habitat. The memorandum directs specific actions to be taken, such as publishing an analysis of the economic impacts of the proposed rule, considering exclusions, and developing clear direction for evaluating logging activity in critical habitat areas. The memorandum concludes by stating that it does not create any enforceable rights or benefits.